I've noticed that there are three categories of errors that need to be handled somewhat differently

- Errors during initialization
	- Bad paths
	- Error in mod_api
	- Game function registration
	
- Compilation errors
- Runtime errors

Initialization errors can't really be handled. They happen at startup and they
need to be resolved manually for most games. 

Compile time errors can be provided entirely by the grug_state, and it will
happen in the regular course of the game. The errors need to be communicated to
the user. We need lots of extra context and diagnostics and maybe suggestions too.

Right now, we handle runtime errors with runtime_error_handler. We don't get
much information about the error except the script and which on_ function was
last called. Right now we don't pass debug info in the ast, so we can't get much info back

Each of these three should probably be handled separately. 

- Initialization errors probably only need an error code and message (maybe mod_api errors need more?)

- Compile errors should have the error code, message, surrounding context, diagnostics, and suggestions
struct grug_compile_error {
	void* allocator;
	enum grug_compile_error_kind kind;
	// one line error string. This can be printed to the console.
	char* error_string;
	// Use these for more structured error reporting
	char* file_path;
	char* err_code;
	struct grug_span err_span;
	char* file_text;
	// Extra information to make debugging easier
	struct grug_compile_error_help* help;
	size_t help_len;
}

- Runtime errors should ideally have span information from the location of the error


